SIMPLE: humorist
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Humorist
<hw>Hu"mor*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>humoriste</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>One who
attributes diseases of the state of the humors.</def>
<mark>[archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who has some peculiarity or eccentricity of
character, which he indulges in odd or whimsical ways.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He [Roger de Coverley] . . . was a great <qex>humorist</qex> in
all parts of his life.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who displays humor in speaking or writing; one
who has a facetious fancy or genius; a wag; a droll; especially, one who
writes or tells jokes as a profession.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The reputation of wits and <qex>humorists</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Humoristic</ent>⟦br⟧
